label: Speech to Text
info: In this example we perform speech to text processing by obtaining a sample fragment of speech as a WAV file.  This is retrieved over the Internet and then passed into the GCP text to speech node.  The results are logged to the debug window.

label: Region
tooltip: Select a region of the nodes storing these files

name: Country
label: Country
tooltip: Select a country of the nodes storing these files

label: City
tooltip: Select a city of the nodes storing these files

name: Remove layer
func:
msg.payload = {command:{clear:"Terrain"}};
return msg;

label: Clear
tooltip: Clear all nodes from the map

func:
msg.payload = {"command":{"clear":"unknown"}}
return msg;

clock
info:
<script id="titleScript" type="text/javascript">

$(function() {
    if($('.md-toolbar-tools').length != 0){
        loadClock();
    }else setTimeout(loadClock, 500)
});

function loadClock(){
    $('#clock').remove();
    var toolbar = $('.md-toolbar-tools');
    
    var div = $('<div/>');
    var p = $('<p/ id="clock">');
    
    div.append(p);
    div[0].style.margin = '5px 5px 5px auto';
    toolbar.append(div);

    function displayTitle(lh) {
        p.text(lh); 
    }
    
    function upTime() {
        var d = new Date();
        p.text(d.toLocaleString());
    }

    if(document.clockInterval){ 
            clearInterval(document.clockInterval);
            document.clockInterval = null;
    }
        
    document.clockInterval = setInterval(upTime,1000);
}

</script>

name: driving policy intent
template:
Keep Your Hands on the Wheel at the Proper Positions: Keep your hands lower, at either 9 and 3 or 8 and 4. This gives you more control and stability when driving, and is also the most ergonomic position to hold your hands for long periods of time.
Adjust Your Mirrors to Cover Your Blind Spots: Adjust the side mirrors so far outward so they're just overlapping your rear-view mirror. Don't Have Your Car Visible Anywhere in Your Mirrors
Don't Drive When You're Drowsy - Nearly 25% Of Fatal Crashes Involve A Drowsy Driver. Any time your mental facilities could be compromised—whether from alcohol, poor sleep, new medication, or even having a horrible cold—is a time to stay off the road or find an alternative to driving.
Avoid Distractions, Be focused: The focus of any driver, at all times, should be driving. Distracted driving is anything that takes your attention away from driving. The most obvious forms of distraction are cell phone use, texting while driving, eating and drinking.
Don’t drink and drive, Be responsible. Illegal drugs, as well as prescription and over-the-counter medications, can be just as deadly on the road as alcohol. If you plan to drink, designate a sober driver before going out. I can call you a taxi or call one of your friends If you are already drunk.
Don't Speed: speeding is  a contributing factor in fatal crashes, millions of lives were lost in speeding-related crashes
Wear Your Seat Belt. it saves lives by preventing you from being thrown around the inside of a crashing vehicle or, worse, thrown through the windshield and flung completely out of the vehicle
Be Extra Careful in Bad Weather. If you're driving through fog, heavy rain, a snow storm or on icy roads, be extra cautious. Drive below the speed limit if necessary, maintain extra space between you and the car ahead, and be especially careful around curves.
Maintaining a safe distance. Drivers need enough time to react if that car makes a sudden turn. I recommend The three-second rule: Find a stationary object on the side of the road. When the car ahead of you passes it, start counting seconds. At least three seconds should pass before your car passes the same object
Watch Out for the Other Guy. Sometimes, it doesn't matter how safely you drive. Make sure you check your mirrors and keep an eye on side streets so you'll know which other cars are around you and how they're driving.
Keep Your Vehicle Safe. Vehicle maintenance is a major safety issue. Check tire pressure, car's brakes, safety recalls and so on.
